this is 22 (i guess)! 

i’ve always thought of birthday posts as a nice yearly check-in. this year is no exception. 

i loved being 21 and loved the life and woman that was created this year.
21 was a year of saying “yes” to learning how to love more well and fully. i fell in love and fell out of it and found that my friends are the best relationship in my life. they are generous by default and passionate about their work— they have made my world bigger. people ask if i’m in love and i tell them about my wonderful friends— the people who keep me afloat when my anxiety and depression get the best of me. 

oh! in my 21st year of life, i got medicated for those things and it was one of the best decisions of my life. don’t be afraid to go to therapy or be on an SSRI— we must continue to talk about mental health to break the stigma!! 

i want to acknowledge the pain of this year of life too. growing up is so confusing and if you feel the same way, you’re not alone! “one thing i do know is that we have to be kind—especially when we don’t know what’s going on” find the humanity in others and connect yours to theirs. talk to your friends about how the heartbreaking and scary things in our world make you feel—especially right now. hope is hard to find sometimes. stay close to the people that feel like hope. 

if you’re turning 21 this year the best advice i’d give is to have more open and candid 2 am calls with people you trust. you’ll never regret them but i’m sorry to your sleep schedule in advance. 

here’s to 22..ooh ooh! (cue the track!)

and because you know i love to write a sappy caption: 

in 5th grade we gave an auditorium room style presentation about ourselves. one of the questions we had to answer was what we wanted to be when we grew up. in-front of my classmates and their parents i said that i wanted to be an actress. a few people laughed at such a far fetched dream—my mom shrugged her shoulders and knew this was all a part of something bigger. 

last night, i looked around at the lights and decorations and realized my dreams of having career as an asian american actress is my current reality. i wouldn’t be here without the sacrifice of my friends and family. it takes a village and a damn big one at that. i’m nervous and excited and optimistically cautious. there apparently isn’t a “how to cope with the anxiety of your dreams coming true at 22 for dummies” but i think my friends and team could write one.  i’m so honoured, this moment does not escape me for a second. see you on the 17th❤️

#bts #loveintaipei #loveboattaipei ✨@abigailhingwen: Filming the Loveboat book adaptation in Taipei together was a truly magical experience. We filmed when the world was still social distancing and the borders of Taiwan were closed, but after a strict two week quarantine, we were free to live life as normal. We had a blast roaming Taipei with the sets as well as on our own. The gorgeous Grand Hotel where the party scene takes place also happened to be our very last night of filming — we did it! ✨

Love in Taipei stars @ashleyjliao (of #balladofsongbirdsandsnakes) @rossbutler @nicotheduffer @chelseatzhang and is based on @abigailhingwen’s New York Times best selling novel Loveboat, Taipei, with the journey continuing in the companion novels Loveboat Reunion and Loveboat Forever. The film is now out on ParamountPlus, AmazonPrime, AppleTV, Vudu and YouTube!
